{"TopicId":149226,"ForumId":16,"TopicTitle":"\u0026quot;geosynchronous\u0026quot; polar orbit","CreatedByName":"BigFatStupidHead","CreatedById":44217,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-10-03T21:41:59Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"BigFatStupidHead","CreatedById":44217,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-10-03T21:41:59Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nHey folks,\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\u00A0 I want to set up a polar satellite that revolves at the same speed as Kerbin, so that it is always passing over the same parts of Kerbin. How do I set this up?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Stargate525","CreatedById":53585,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-10-03T21:47:11Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nYou calculate the orbital period (the amount of time it takes to make a complete orbit), and make it match a multiple of 6 hours. That way it\u0027ll sync up with the planet\u0027s rotation in some manner. If you want it 1:1, you put a satellite into a regular geosync orbit, but rotated 90 degrees.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"IronCretin","CreatedById":158162,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-10-03T21:48:04Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nDo these help?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tundra_orbit\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tundra_orbit\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molniya_orbit\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molniya_orbit\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"BigFatStupidHead","CreatedById":44217,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-10-03T21:53:02Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222785934\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022149226\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221475531231\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002253585\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Stargate525\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n4 minutes ago, Stargate525 said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nYou calculate the orbital period (the amount of time it takes to make a complete orbit), and make it match a multiple of 6 hours. That way it\u0027ll sync up with the planet\u0027s rotation in some manner. If you want it 1:1, you put a satellite into a regular geosync orbit, but rotated 90 degrees.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nOk, so a 1:1 polar geosync orbit will still have an altitude of ~2886750m. Thanks!\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222785936\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022149226\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221475531284\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022158162\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022IronCretin\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n3 minutes ago, IronCretin said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nDo these help?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tundra_orbit\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tundra_orbit\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molniya_orbit\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molniya_orbit\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI\u0027d never heard of the Tundra orbit before, but I do use Molniya orbits. Good stuff.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Stargate525","CreatedById":53585,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-10-04T01:43:50Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222785940\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022149226\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221475531582\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002244217\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022BigFatStupidHead\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n3 hours ago, BigFatStupidHead said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nOk, so a 1:1 polar geosync orbit will still have an altitude of ~2886750m. Thanks!\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIt should. It should trace a circle over the map, I...think.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Chiron0224","CreatedById":147812,"CreatedDateTime":"2016-10-05T20:25:19Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00222786233\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022149226\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221475545430\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002253585\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Stargate525\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\nOn \u200E10\u200E/\u200E3\u200E/\u200E2016 at 9:43 PM, Stargate525 said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nIt should. It should trace a circle over the map, I...think.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI think it will make a figure 8 from the perspective of a given point on Kerbin\u0027s surface\u00A0if I\u0027m not mistaken.\u00A0 I think I\u0027ll give this a try once I finish riding out this damned hurricane that\u0027s headed right for us (I live in Jacksonville Fl).\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"}]}